50|$|If {{the time}} to appeal {{in the court of}} origin has lapsed, and the {{judgment}} has become final, the holder of a <b>foreign</b> <b>judgment,</b> decree or order may file suit before a competent court in the U.S. which will determine whether to give effect to the <b>foreign</b> <b>judgment.</b> A local version of the Uniform Foreign Money Judgments Recognition Act applies in most states, for example in California. 13 U.L.A. 149 (1986).|$|E
50|$|In law, the {{enforcement}} of <b>foreign</b> <b>judgments</b> is the recognition and enforcement in one jurisdiction of judgments rendered in another ("foreign") jurisdiction. <b>Foreign</b> <b>judgments</b> may be recognized based on bilateral or multilateral treaties or understandings, or unilaterally without an express international agreement.|$|R
